<hl>
<seg id=1> China To Put Million Tons Of Landfill Along Coast Next Century In Arrangements For 20 To 30 Million People </seg>
</hl>
<p>
<seg id=2> (AGENCE FRANCE PRESSE WIRE Beijing) The English language newspaper China Daily reported yesterday that China plans to reclaim land along the coastal region for 20 to 30 million people in the next century. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=3> Experts holding an earthfill conference in Xiaoshan in Zhejiang province revealed that the government hopes to fill in one million tons of earth along 18 thousand kilometers of the coast in the next 40 to 50 years. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=4> China Daily said that 20 to 30 million people will be able to live in these areas in the next century. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=5> Professor Yu Zhiyan (through an interpreter) was quoted in the newspaper as saying, "In terms of technology, China won't have a problem with the actual landfill itself. The problem will be with insufficient funding." </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=6> The news said that even though the project will cause a large environmental problem, "It will be the trick that eases the next century's problem of insufficient land resources, especially in view of China's large population." </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=7> The project will also promote new industry and employment. </seg>
<seg id=8> China has invested in infrastructure in order to mitigate the effects of the Asian financial crisis. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=9> Zuo Zhongmo, assistant secretary-general for the conference, said (through an interpreter), "This is not only an agricultural issue, this land will provide more territory for comprehensive development use, including forestry, industry and tourism." </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=10> Even though China promotes its "One Child Policy", China's population is expected to continue growing until the middle of the next century when it will peak at 1.6 billion. </seg>
<seg id=11> China's current population is 1.23 billion. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=12> More than 90 percent of the population is compacted into one-third of the country's territory. </seg>
</p>
